    "narrative_summary": "The BRCA2 missense change p.L209F (c.625C>T) occurs in the breast\u2011ovarian cancer susceptibility gene and has been evaluated in the context of hereditary breast and ovarian cancer risk [PMC6134256]. No clinical case reports, segregation analyses, or formal clinical classifications for this variant are presented in the supplied literature.\n\nFunctional assessment of the variant using a splice\u2011reporter assay found no aberrant splicing, and the authors interpreted the result as supporting a benign effect [PMC4907813]. In a separate comprehensive annotation of BRCA2 missense changes, the same variant was placed in functional class C0, a category consistent with a neutral impact on protein function [PMC6287763].\n\nIn silico analyses further reinforce a benign interpretation. A study that evaluated multiple computational predictors assigned the variant a benign classification based on scores from tools such as MutationTaster, PolyPhen\u20112, and others [PMC9213547]. An earlier evaluation of splicing prediction tools included the variant in a validation set but did not attribute any pathogenicity claim, consistent with a lack of evidence for deleterious splicing effects [PMC6134256]. The variant is also listed among BRCA2 alterations observed in a large Chinese cohort, without any indication of pathogenic relevance [PMC6617753].\n\nTaken together, the available functional data showing no splice disruption, the neutral functional class assignment, and the concordant benign predictions from multiple computational platforms provide consistent evidence that BRCA2 p.L209F is not pathogenic. No conflicting data were identified, and the preponderance of evidence supports a benign classification for this variant.",
